HEADWORD: Tetrapla
<hw>Tet"ra*pla</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<note>etymologically <pos>pl.</pos>, but syntactically
<pos>sing.</pos></note> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>tetraplo`os</grk>,
<grk>tetraploy^s</grk>, fourfold.]</ety> <def>A Bible consisting of four
different Greek versions arranged in four columns by
<persfn>Origen</persfn>; hence, any version in four languages or four
columns.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

